42    /**
43    * Inline variables when possible. Using the information from
44    * {@link MaybeReachingVariableUse} and {@link MustBeReachingVariableDef},
45    * this pass attempts to inline a variable by placing the value at the
46    * definition where the variable is used. The basic requirements for inlining
47    * are the following:
48    *
49    * <ul>
50    * <li> There is exactly one reaching definition at the use of that variable
51    * </li>
52    * <li> There is exactly one use for that definition of the variable
53    * </li>
54    * </ul>
55    *
56    * <p>Other requirements can be found in {@link Candidate#canInline}. Currently
57    * this pass does not operate on the global scope due to compilation time.
58    *
59    */
 
86.7% Uncovered Elements: 11 (83) Complexity: 27 Complexity Density: 0.63
60    class FlowSensitiveInlineVariables extends AbstractPostOrderCallback
61    implements CompilerPass, ScopedCallback {
62   
63    /**
64    * Implementation:
65    *
66    * This pass first perform a traversal to gather a list of Candidates that
67    * could be inlined using {@link GatherCandiates}.
68    *
69    * The second step involves verifying that each candidate is actually safe
70    * to inline with {@link Candidate#canInline(Scope)} and finally perform
71    * inlining using {@link Candidate#inlineVariable()}.
72    *
73    * The reason for the delayed evaluation of the candidates is because we
74    * need two separate dataflow result.
75    */
76    private final AbstractCompiler compiler;
77    private final Set<Var> inlinedNewDependencies = Sets.newHashSet();
78   
79    // These two pieces of data is persistent in the whole execution of enter
80    // scope.
81    private ControlFlowGraph<Node> cfg;
82    private List<Candidate> candidates;
83    private MustBeReachingVariableDef reachingDef;
84    private MaybeReachingVariableUse reachingUses;
85
